menu "Tracker"

config TRACKER_LOG_LEVEL
	int "Compiled-in log level (0=off 1=ERR 2=WRN 3=INF 4=DBG)"
	default 4
	range 0 4
	help
	  The ceiling COMPILED INTO the binary for the tracker's own modules —
	  levels above it do not exist at runtime and no backend or shell
	  command can bring them back. 4 keeps the DBG chatter (status blocks,
	  satellite tables, RRC edges) available: UART shows it by default and
	  the shell can silence it; the uplink backend has its own quieter
	  threshold (TRACKER_LOG_UPLINK_LEVEL) so none of it hits the wire.

config TRACKER_POST_INTERVAL_S
	int "GPS sample interval in seconds"
	default 1
	range 1 3600
	help
	  How often a GPS fix is queued while reporting. 1 Hz matches the GNSS
	  PVT rate and costs ~7 B/point on the wire as track-segment deltas;
	  the flush cadence, not this, decides how often the radio wakes.

config TRACKER_GPS_STALE_S
	int "Seconds since last GPS fix before it's considered stale (use cell)"
	default 30
	range 10 3600

config TRACKER_SERVER_HOST
	string "CoAP server hostname or IP"
	default "127.0.0.1"
	help
	  Where observations are POSTed (coap://HOST:PORT/obs). The default suits
	  the native_sim demo; hardware builds set it via .env
	  (TRACKER_SERVER_HOST).

config TRACKER_SERVER_PORT
	int "CoAP server UDP port"
	default 5683
	range 1 65535

config TRACKER_LOC_CN0_MIN_DBHZ
	int "C/N0 floor for a satellite to count as usable (dB-Hz)"
	default 27
	range 15 45
	help
	  Below roughly 27 dB-Hz a satellite can be tracked but its navigation
	  message cannot be demodulated, so it never yields an ephemeris. Used to
	  decide whether the sky is worth taking the radio away from LTE for.

config TRACKER_FLUSH_INTERVAL_S
	int "Uplink flush interval in seconds"
	default 120
	range 10 3600
	help
	  The slow-path timer: uplink drains all sources at least this often
	  when the radio is allowed. Fullness and urgent events flush sooner.

config TRACKER_LOG_UPLINK_LEVEL
	int "Max log level shipped over LTE (1=ERR 2=WRN 3=INF 4=DBG)"
	default 3
	range 1 4
	help
	  Lines at or below this level are queued for uplink delivery. INF is
	  deliberately quiet (a handful of lines per 10 min); DBG would be
	  chatty and is meant for UART/shell use.

config TRACKER_LOG_WAKE_MIN_S
	int "Minimum seconds between log-triggered radio wakes"
	default 60
	range 5 3600
	help
	  A WRN+ log line requests an urgent uplink flush; this rate limit
	  stops an error loop from chattering the radio (and starving GNSS).

config TRACKER_LOG_UPLINK_RING_LINES
	int "Log-uplink ring capacity (lines)"
	default 128
	range 16 1024
	help
	  How many log lines queue in RAM while the radio is unavailable
	  (LTE outage, GNSS_EXCLUSIVE). ~120 B per line. Overflow drops the
	  oldest and reports the count in-band; the flash flight recorder
	  (phase 2) is the durable tier.

config TRACKER_CELL_POST_INTERVAL_S
	int "Cell publish interval while GNSS has no usable sky (seconds)"
	default 30
	range 15 3600
	help
	  Deliberately slower than the normal publish interval: the gaps between
	  cell publishes are what let GNSS observe satellites, so leaving that
	  no-sky state is signal-driven rather than a blind retry timer. Below
	  ~15 s the gaps are too short for GNSS to sense anything.

config TRACKER_LOC_ACQUIRE_TIMEOUT_S
	int "Give up a quiet GNSS acquisition window after this long"
	default 300
	range 60 1800
	help
	  Bounds how long the tracker may go silent hunting ephemeris under a
	  partial sky. A product decision, not a technical one: cold start may
	  simply never complete indoors.

config TRACKER_LOC_SKY_EMPTY_EPOCHS
	int "Observed epochs with zero satellites before declaring the sky empty"
	default 5
	range 2 60
	help
	  Counted only over epochs where GNSS actually had the radio (blanked
	  epochs count toward neither verdict). Abandons an acquisition under a
	  truly empty sky (indoors, Faraday cage); a 30 s cold-start grace at
	  acquisition entry keeps a warming receiver from tripping it.

config TRACKER_MOTION_RADIUS_M
	int "Parked radius in metres"
	default 25
	range 10 200
	help
	  A fix farther than this from the parked centroid means the device
	  moved. Must sit above open-sky GPS jitter (~5-15 m) with margin;
	  below ~25 m indoor multipath causes spurious wakes (each one costs
	  a radio wake and a 5-minute re-entry wait, nothing worse).

config TRACKER_MOTION_ENTRY_S
	int "Seconds of dwell before declaring the device stationary"
	default 300
	range 60 3600
	help
	  Hysteresis against premature quiescence: getting a bike ready for
	  a ride is a few minutes of standing still and must not park the
	  tracker. Exit needs no hysteresis (one out-of-radius fix wakes it).

config TRACKER_QUIESCENT_CHECK_S
	int "Parked-with-fix position check interval (seconds)"
	default 120
	range 30 3600
	help
	  GNSS periodic-mode interval while parked with a held fix. Each
	  check is a hot start (1-3 s awake); the next check after the bike
	  moves is what detects theft, so this bounds detection latency.

config TRACKER_QUIESCENT_FLUSH_S
	int "Uplink flush interval while parked (seconds)"
	default 1200
	range 120 7200
	help
	  Radio wakes are the parked data cost (47 B datagram overhead plus
	  RRC signalling); 20 min x ~30 B check points ~= 25 KB/day parked
	  vs ~600 KB/day at the moving cadence. Motion still flushes
	  urgently via the FSM state change.

config TRACKER_SIM_DEVICE_ID
	string "native_sim fallback device ID"
	default "sim-dev-1"
	help
	  Used by the native_sim hw_id_get() stub when the TRACKER_DEVICE_ID
	  environment variable is unset. Ignored on hardware (IMEI is used).

endmenu

menu "Zephyr Kernel"
source "Kconfig.zephyr"
endmenu
